# BunSetup

This project was generated using [Angular CLI](https://github.com/angular/angular-cli) version 21.1.2.

## Development server

To start a local development server, run:

```bash
bun run start
```

Once the server is running, open your browser and navigate to `http://localhost:4200/`. The application will automatically reload whenever you modify any of the source files.

Note: The scripts force Bun and set `NG_BUILD_PARTIAL_SSR=1` to avoid the Node-only in-memory SSR loader used by the Angular CLI.

## Auth0 server-side auth

This app uses a BFF-style Auth0 flow that works without JavaScript. All routes are server-rendered and receive an optional auth session when available. Configure these environment variables:

- `AUTH0_DOMAIN` (required)
- `AUTH0_CLIENT_ID` (required)
- `AUTH0_CLIENT_SECRET` (required)
- `AUTH0_BASE_URL` (optional, defaults to request origin)
- `AUTH0_AUDIENCE` (optional)
- `AUTH0_SCOPE` (optional, defaults to `openid profile email`)
- `AUTH0_LOGIN_PATH` (optional, defaults to `/auth/login`)
- `AUTH0_CALLBACK_PATH` (optional, defaults to `/auth/callback`)
- `AUTH0_LOGOUT_PATH` (optional, defaults to `/auth/logout`)
- `AUTH0_SESSION_COOKIE` (optional, defaults to `app_session`)
- `AUTH0_SESSION_TTL_SECONDS` (optional, caps token lifetime)
- `AUTH0_TRANSACTION_TTL_SECONDS` (optional, defaults to `600`)

## Code scaffolding

Angular CLI includes powerful code scaffolding tools. To generate a new component, run:

```bash
bun run ng generate component component-name
```

For a complete list of available schematics (such as `components`, `directives`, or `pipes`), run:

```bash
bun run ng generate --help
```

## Building

To build the project run:

```bash
bun run build
```

This will compile your project and store the build artifacts in the `dist/` directory. By default, the production build optimizes your application for performance and speed.

## Running unit tests

To execute unit tests with the [Vitest](https://vitest.dev/) test runner, use the following command:

```bash
bun run test
```

## Running end-to-end tests

For end-to-end (e2e) testing, run:

```bash
bun run ng e2e
```

Angular CLI does not come with an end-to-end testing framework by default. You can choose one that suits your needs.

## Additional Resources

